- Cloudflare dry-run must be true by default.
- Notifications dry-run must be true by default.
- Worker system can run locally with Redis.
- Tenant isolation must work in SQLite and PostgreSQL.
- No secret may be logged or exposed in frontend.

============================================================
MULTI-TENANT REQUIREMENTS
============================================================

Create tenant system:

Entities:

1. Organization
- id
- name
- slug
- owner_user_id
- status
- created_at
- updated_at

2. Workspace
- id
- organization_id
- name
- slug
- environment
- status
- created_at
- updated_at

3. OrganizationMember
- id
- organization_id
- user_id
- role
- status
- created_at
- updated_at

4. WorkspaceMember
- id
- workspace_id
- user_id
- role
- status
- created_at
- updated_at

Statuses:
- active
- suspended
- archived

Workspace environments:
- development
- staging
- production
- simulation

Requirements:
- Every persisted business record must include organization_id and workspace_id where applicable.
- Risk state, scheduler jobs, backtest results, content items, IoT logs, and audit logs must be tenant-scoped.
- Default local org/workspace must be bootstrapped automatically in development.
- Existing single-tenant data must map to default org/workspace.
- APIs must resolve tenant context from:
  1. explicit route/path param when provided
  2. request headers
  3. user’s default org/workspace
  4. development fallback default org/workspace

Tenant isolation:
- Non-admin users can only access organizations/workspaces where they are members.
- Admin can access all tenants.
- Operator/analyst/viewer permissions are scoped to membership.
- Cross-tenant access must return 403.

============================================================
TENANT API REQUIREMENTS
============================================================

Create:

GET /api/tenancy/context

Returns current organization/workspace context.

GET /api/tenancy/organizations

Lists organizations current user can access.

POST /api/tenancy/organizations

Creates organization.

GET /api/tenancy/organizations/{org_id}

Returns organization details.

PATCH /api/tenancy/organizations/{org_id}

Updates organization.

GET /api/tenancy/organizations/{org_id}/workspaces

Lists workspaces.

POST /api/tenancy/organizations/{org_id}/workspaces

Creates workspace.

GET /api/tenancy/workspaces/{workspace_id}

Returns workspace.

PATCH /api/tenancy/workspaces/{workspace_id}

Updates workspace.

POST /api/tenancy/organizations/{org_id}/members

Adds user to organization.

POST /api/tenancy/workspaces/{workspace_id}/members

Adds user to workspace.

Rules:
- Use standard API response shape.
- Tenant admin actions require admin or organization owner.
- Audit all tenant admin changes.

============================================================
WORKER QUEUE REQUIREMENTS
============================================================

Create queue system:

Task types:

- trading_scan
- risk_check
- backtest_run
- optimization_run
- content_pipeline_run
- content_publish_dry_run
- iot_status_check
- notification_dispatch
- audit_compaction
- backup_run
- custom

Models:

1. WorkerTask
- id
- organization_id
- workspace_id
- task_type
- status
- payload
- result
- error
- priority
- attempts
- max_retries
- scheduled_at
- started_at
- finished_at
- created_at
- updated_at

Statuses:
- queued
- running
- completed
- failed
- retrying
- cancelled

2. WorkerStatus
- worker_id
- hostname
- status
- current_task_id
- processed_count
- failed_count
- last_heartbeat_at

Implement:

backend/app/workers/queue.py

Methods:
- enqueue(task_type, payload, tenant_context, priority=5) -> WorkerTask
- dequeue(worker_id) -> WorkerTask | None
- complete(task_id, result) -> WorkerTask
- fail(task_id, error) -> WorkerTask
- retry(task_id) -> WorkerTask
- cancel(task_id) -> WorkerTask
- list_tasks(filters) -> list[WorkerTask]

Implement Redis-backed queue if Redis is available.
Fallback to in-memory queue if Redis unavailable in development.

Worker behavior:
- Never crash entire worker on task failure.
- Capture task result/error.
- Respect tenant context.
- Respect Guardian risk checks.
- Respect content approval checks.
- Respect IoT dry-run rules.
- Respect social dry-run rules.

============================================================
WORKER API REQUIREMENTS
============================================================

Create:

GET /api/workers/status

Returns worker queue status.

GET /api/workers/tasks

Lists tasks for current tenant.

POST /api/workers/tasks

Enqueues task.

POST /api/workers/tasks/{task_id}/cancel

Cancels queued task.

POST /api/workers/tasks/{task_id}/retry

Retries failed task.

GET /api/workers/tasks/{task_id}

Returns task detail.

Rules:
- All routes require auth.
- Tenant scoped.
- Enqueue requires permission based on task type.
- Audit task enqueue/cancel/retry.

============================================================
REALTIME EVENT STREAM REQUIREMENTS
============================================================

Add WebSocket support:

Endpoint:

WS /api/realtime/events

Features:
- Auth via token query param or Authorization-compatible handshake.
- Tenant-scoped event stream.
- Sends recent buffered events on connect.
- Streams new events live.
- Supports event category filter.
- Sends heartbeat ping.
- Cleans up disconnected clients.

Event categories:
- system
- agent
- trading
- risk
- scheduler
- worker
- iot
- backtest
- content
- auth
- audit
- notification

Frontend:
- Add live event indicator.
- Session Logs page should support WebSocket mode.
- Fallback to polling if WebSocket fails.

============================================================
NOTIFICATION AND ALERT REQUIREMENTS
============================================================

Create alert system.

AlertRule:
- id
- organization_id
- workspace_id
- name
- event_type
- severity
- enabled
- condition
- channels
- created_at
- updated_at

AlertEvent:
- id
- organization_id
- workspace_id
- rule_id
- severity
- title
- message
- payload
- status
- created_at

NotificationChannel:
- id
- organization_id
- workspace_id
- name
- channel_type
- enabled
- config
- created_at
- updated_at

Channel types:
- dry_run
- email
- webhook

Default alert rules:
- risk emergency stop triggered
- risk halt activated
- worker task failed
- scheduler job failed
- content publish blocked
- IoT action blocked
- auth login failure spike
- production safety blocker

Notification service:
- In dry-run mode, record notification but do not send.
- Email channel must be stubbed unless SMTP configured.
- Webhook channel must be stubbed unless WEBHOOK_NOTIFICATIONS_ENABLED=true.
- Never send secrets in notification payloads.

